+# Repository access and reconnaissance record
+
+## Connector test
+
+GitHub connector access was explicitly tested on 2026-07-13 before repository claims or write actions were made.
+
+Confirmed through the authenticated connector:
+
+- `karadzhyan/hotel-wage-law-v2` is accessible, uses `main`, and the connected account has administrative and push permissions.
+- `karadzhyan/hotel-wage-hour` is accessible as a private repository, uses `main`, and the connected account has administrative and push permissions.
+- The v2 repository was empty at the start of publication.
+- The connector exposes repository read operations and Git data / contents write operations required to initialize and maintain the v2 repository.
+
+## Reference-repository reconnaissance
+
+The following implementation characteristics were confirmed from the private reference repository's current README and indexed files:
+
+- zero-dependency Node static-site generator
+- source under `src/`, generated GitHub Pages output under `docs/`, and verification research under `research/`
+- data-driven state, ordinance, case, glossary, FAQ, development, calendar, and calculation records
+- 18 issue briefs, 51 state and District of Columbia guides, 19 hotel-specific law records, and 10 interactive tools
+- deterministic build, calculator and template tests, internal-link and semantic checks, staleness reporting, and print-optimized audit materials
+- key migration surfaces including `build.js`, `data/SCHEMA.md`, `lib/`, `src/content/`, `src/assets/`, `test/`, and `research/`
+
+The repository snapshot surfaced by the connector was anchored to commit `74fa16e9dd4b09920b039defa6a3ff4205494210`; the fetched README blob was `c5b8ce406b3a88d3c6e4671b7c65a75abdca3760`.
+
+## Audit boundary
+
+This record is reconnaissance, not a completed file-by-file legal, data, calculator, SEO, accessibility, or security audit. Production migration must still inventory and map:
+
+1. every canonical URL and redirect requirement
+2. every source and passage locator
+3. every data field and effective interval
+4. every calculator branch, parameter, fixture, and limitation
+5. every research memo and unresolved verification gap
+6. every generated artifact and deployment assumption
+7. every analytics, privacy, accessibility, and security dependency
+8. every reusable component versus migration liability
+
+## Publication record
+
+The canonical v2 source is intended to live in `karadzhyan/hotel-wage-law-v2`. GitHub Actions provide build verification and a review-only Pages deployment. Repository state, commits, workflow runs, and deployment status must be verified from connector responses before being represented as complete.
diff --git a/product/SECURITY-PRIVACY.md b/product/SECURITY-PRIVACY.md
new file mode 100644
index 0000000..65b63cd
--- /dev/null
+++ b/product/SECURITY-PRIVACY.md
@@ -0,0 +1,135 @@
+# Security, privilege, and privacy architecture
+
+## Threat model
+
+The platform may contain privileged legal advice, litigation-sensitive analysis, employee-level payroll facts, health-benefit information, vendor data, and executive decisions. The security model must therefore assume that unauthorized disclosure could create legal, financial, employment, and reputational harm.
+
+Primary threats include:
+
+- cross-tenant data exposure
+- privilege leakage through search or AI retrieval
+- overbroad portfolio access
+- unauthorized export of evidence or decision records
+- source or rule tampering
+- silent alteration of approved records
+- prompt injection in external source material
+- employee-data overcollection
+- stale permissions after organizational changes
+- insecure third-party integrations
+
+## Public/private boundary
+
+Public authority and enterprise work may share identifiers and data structures, but not storage or authorization assumptions.
+
+Public plane:
+
+- published sources and canonical analysis
+- public jurisdiction and issue content
+- public tools with non-customer inputs
+
+Private plane:
+
+- property and workforce facts
+- matters and counsel analysis
+- scenarios, findings, controls, evidence, decisions
+- customer-specific search and AI context
+
+A public request must never inherit private context merely because the user is authenticated elsewhere.
+
+## Tenant isolation
+
+Recommended controls:
+
+- tenant key on every private record
+- tenant-scoped database policies
+- object storage prefixes and encryption boundaries
+- tenant-aware search indices
+- tenant-aware background jobs and caches
+- automated cross-tenant negative tests
+- support access through time-bound, approved impersonation
+
+## Authorization
+
+Use role-based access as a baseline and attribute-based rules for sensitive work.
+
+Attributes may include:
+
+- tenant
+- business unit
+- property cluster
+- matter team
+- privilege designation
+- data classification
+- region
+- legal hold
+- employment role
+
+Permissions should be evaluated server-side for every object, export, retrieval, and AI context assembly.
+
+## Privilege
+
+Matter records should support:
+
+- attorney-client and work-product designations
+- purpose and counsel involvement
+- distribution restrictions
+- separate factual and advice layers
+- privilege-aware search and exports
+- audit history
+- legal holds
+- configurable waiver warnings
+
+The product must not imply that merely storing an item in a “legal” system creates privilege.
+
+## Data minimization
+
+Applicability should prefer cohorts and governed facts over raw employee records. Employee-level data should be used only when required for calculations, remediation, or evidence, and should have:
+
+- purpose limitation
+- field minimization
+- retention periods
+- masking
+- access logging
+- deletion workflows subject to legal hold
+
+## Evidence integrity
+
+Evidence items should preserve:
+
+- source system
+- collection timestamp
+- period and population
+- content hash
+- uploader or automated collector
+- transformations
+- reviewer and acceptance state
+- retention classification
+
+Immutable event history should record changes to findings, controls, decisions, and approvals.
+
+## AI and retrieval security
+
+- isolate public and private retrieval indices
+- enforce permissions before retrieval, not after generation
+- treat source content as untrusted input
+- neutralize prompt-injection instructions in retrieved documents
+- log material prompts, retrieved objects, model/version, and response metadata
+- prevent models from training on tenant data unless explicitly contracted and controlled
+- redact high-risk personal data before model invocation where possible
+- provide an abstention path when evidence or permissions are insufficient
+
+## Baseline production controls
+
+- SSO/SAML and SCIM
+- MFA and conditional access
+- encryption in transit and at rest
+- secrets management
+- secure SDLC and dependency scanning
+- vulnerability management and penetration testing
+- centralized audit logs and SIEM integration
+- incident response and breach workflows
+- backups and tested recovery
+- regional/data-residency options where required
+- vendor risk management
+- privacy impact assessments
+- WCAG 2.2 AA accessibility program
diff --git a/product/VISUAL-SYSTEM.md b/product/VISUAL-SYSTEM.md
new file mode 100644
index 0000000..bfe2a94
--- /dev/null
+++ b/product/VISUAL-SYSTEM.md
@@ -0,0 +1,185 @@
+# Visual system
+
+## Design position
+
+Hotel Wage Law should look neither like a law-firm brochure nor like a generic SaaS dashboard. The visual system is an **institutional operating interface**: authoritative enough for cited legal work, operational enough for payroll and property leaders, and concise enough for executive review.
+
+The system should communicate three things before the user reads the copy:
+
+1. the information has hierarchy
+2. the conclusion has a basis
+3. the next action has an owner
+
+## Structural principles
+
+### Hierarchy before decoration
+
+Use scale, placement, grouping, and whitespace to establish order. Borders, shadows, gradients, and color should reinforce that order rather than manufacture it.
+
+### Fewer interchangeable cards
+
+A uniform grid of cards makes every item feel equally important. Prefer purpose-built surfaces:
+
+- decision bands
+- causal chains
+- governed tables
+- evidence stacks
+- exception queues
+- property passports
+- timeline and approval rails
+- source inspectors
+
+Cards remain useful for bounded secondary objects, but they are not the universal layout primitive.
+
+### One visual grammar across public and private planes
+
+The public platform is editorial and spacious. The enterprise plane is denser and operational. They share typography, color semantics, tokens, iconography, and evidence language so a user understands that both are projections of the same governed system.
+
+## Color
+
+The foundation is institutional midnight rather than pure black. Color is semantic, not audience-themed.
+
+| Token family | Meaning | Representative use |
+|---|---|---|
+| Midnight / navy | institutional foundation, navigation, executive context | masthead, enterprise rail, decision bands |
+| Signal blue | change, attention, jurisdiction reach | developments, impact maps, active navigation |
+| Analysis teal | reasoning, scenario, calculated output | models, fact resolution, research traces |
+| Control green | operating effectiveness, accepted evidence, completion | assurance, controls, resolved actions |
+| Authority gold | primary authority, provenance, approval | source chain, evidence standard, decisive CTA |
+| Material red | high-impact exception or invalidation | deadline failure, control exception, material gap |
+| Warm paper | reading and decision-record background | long-form analysis, public editorial sections |
+| Cool neutral | application canvas and supporting structure | tables, secondary panels, inactive states |
+
+Rules:
+
+- never use red to make an ordinary CTA feel urgent
+- never use green merely to make a metric look positive
+- gold identifies authority or decisive focus; it is not a luxury accent applied everywhere
+- mode or department colors must not compete with legal status colors
+- every status color has a text label and icon or shape distinction
+
+## Typography
+
+### Editorial serif
+
+Use the serif face for category statements, direct legal answers, section theses, and decision-record narrative. It signals considered judgment, not nostalgia.
+
+### Interface sans serif
+
+Use the sans serif for navigation, metadata, tables, controls, status, and operational copy. It must remain highly legible at dense sizes.
+
+### Numeric treatment
+
+Tabular numbers are required for rates, dates, exposure ranges, scores, and comparison tables. Every consequential number must display or reveal:
+
+- unit
+- period
+- denominator
+- scope
+- effective date or as-of date
+- whether it is actual, modeled, or illustrative
+
+### Scale behavior
+
+- public hero: large but bounded; it should not consume the entire viewport
+- enterprise page title: direct question or outcome, not product taxonomy
+- section heading: expresses the conclusion of the section
+- labels: sentence case by default
+- uppercase is reserved for compact metadata and overlines, never long prose
+
+## Layout and density
+
+### Public plane
+
+- strong reading rhythm
+- generous section transitions
+- approximately 60–75 character prose measure
+- visual causal models in place of marketing feature grids
+- evidence and limitations close to claims
+
+### Enterprise plane
+
+- persistent context rail
+- primary work surface plus bounded inspector rail where useful
+- tables for comparable records; cards for non-comparable objects
+- sticky actions only when they remain contextual
+- high-value whitespace around decisions, warnings, and legal conclusions
+
+### Responsive behavior
+
+Mobile is a review-and-action surface, not a compressed desktop production environment.
+
+Preserve on mobile:
+
+- active tenant, matter, property, and effective-date context
+- material status and next action
+- source inspection
+- concise findings and approval state
+- large touch targets and keyboard-equivalent controls
+
+Dense matrices remain bounded and horizontally scrollable. Do not force every column into a narrow stack that destroys comparability.
+
+## Data visualization
+
+Visuals should answer a defined operating question.
+
+Approved patterns:
+
+- portfolio reach by jurisdiction or operating cluster
+- obligation-to-control coverage
+- matter lifecycle and aging
+- source-to-decision causal chain
+- effective-date timeline
+- evidence currency and exception distribution
+- scenario range with explicit assumptions
+
+Avoid:
+
+- decorative donuts without denominator and target
+- unlabeled “risk scores”
+- map shading without a legend, date, and coverage definition
+- trend arrows based on incomparable periods
+- precision that exceeds the evidence
+
+## Iconography
+
+Use a consistent SVG line system with restrained stroke weight. Icons identify object type or action; they do not replace labels in consequential workflows.
+
+Representative object metaphors:
+
+- source / authority — document or institutional column
+- change — delta or signal
+- matter — governed file
+- finding — reasoned determination
+- control — shield/check or operating loop
+- evidence — linked artifact
+- decision — approval mark or decision rail
+- property — building passport
+
+## Motion
+
+Motion communicates state change:
+
+- drawers and inspectors entering
+- scope or scenario recalculation
+- filter result updates
+- approval or invalidation state transitions
+
+Motion should be brief, interruptible, and absent under reduced-motion preferences. No ambient animation is necessary to signal sophistication.
+
+## Accessibility baseline
+
+- WCAG 2.2 AA target
+- visible keyboard focus with sufficient contrast
+- semantic landmarks and one primary page heading
+- accessible names for every icon-only control
+- no information conveyed by color alone
+- table headers and captions for data grids
+- error text adjacent to the affected input
+- touch targets sized for mobile use
+- reflow without document-level horizontal overflow
+- zoom and text-resize resilience
+
+## Prototype token source
+
+The implemented token source is [`src/assets/css/tokens.css`](../src/assets/css/tokens.css). Component and layout expressions are distributed across `base.css`, `components.css`, `public.css`, `app.css`, `responsive.css`, and `v2.css`. Production should migrate these values into a documented token package and component library rather than copying page-level CSS ad hoc.
diff --git a/product/schemas/legal-intelligence-graph.schema.json b/product/schemas/legal-intelligence-graph.schema.json
new file mode 100644
index 0000000..a8e4343
--- /dev/null
+++ b/product/schemas/legal-intelligence-graph.schema.json
@@ -0,0 +1,206 @@
+{
+  "$schema": "https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/schema",
+  "$id": "https://hotelwagelaw.com/schemas/legal-intelligence-graph.schema.json",
+  "title": "Hotel Wage Law governed intelligence graph",
+  "description": "Normative contract for the objects that connect legal authority to enterprise decisions. Prototype records may omit production-only security metadata, but may not break lineage.",
+  "type": "object",
+  "required": ["sources", "rules", "changes", "properties", "matters", "findings", "controls", "evidence", "decisions"],
+  "properties": {
+    "sources": {"type": "array", "items": {"$ref": "#/$defs/sourceVersion"}},
+    "rules": {"type": "array", "items": {"$ref": "#/$defs/ruleVersion"}},
+    "changes": {"type": "array", "items": {"$ref": "#/$defs/change"}},
+    "properties": {"type": "array", "items": {"$ref": "#/$defs/property"}},
+    "matters": {"type": "array", "items": {"$ref": "#/$defs/matter"}},
+    "findings": {"type": "array", "items": {"$ref": "#/$defs/finding"}},
+    "controls": {"type": "array", "items": {"$ref": "#/$defs/control"}},
+    "evidence": {"type": "array", "items": {"$ref": "#/$defs/evidenceItem"}},
+    "decisions": {"type": "array", "items": {"$ref": "#/$defs/decisionRecord"}}
+  },
+  "additionalProperties": false,
+  "$defs": {
+    "id": {"type": "string", "pattern": "^[a-z][a-z0-9-]{2,80}$"},
+    "isoDate": {"type": "string", "format": "date"},
+    "isoDateTime": {"type": "string", "format": "date-time"},
+    "status": {"type": "string", "enum": ["draft", "review", "approved", "superseded", "invalidated", "archived"]},
+    "citation": {
+      "type": "object",
+      "required": ["sourceVersionId", "locator"],
+      "properties": {
+        "sourceVersionId": {"$ref": "#/$defs/id"},
+        "locator": {"type": "string", "minLength": 1},
+        "proposition": {"type": "string"},
+        "quotedTextHash": {"type": "string"}
+      },
+      "additionalProperties": false
+    },
+    "sourceVersion": {
+      "type": "object",
+      "required": ["id", "sourceId", "title", "sourceType", "publisher", "retrievedAt", "contentHash", "canonicalUrl"],
+      "properties": {
+        "id": {"$ref": "#/$defs/id"},
+        "sourceId": {"$ref": "#/$defs/id"},
+        "title": {"type": "string", "minLength": 1},
+        "sourceType": {"type": "string", "enum": ["statute", "regulation", "ordinance", "case", "agency-guidance", "official-notice", "secondary-analysis", "customer-evidence"]},
+        "publisher": {"type": "string", "minLength": 1},
+        "jurisdiction": {"type": "string"},
+        "effectiveFrom": {"$ref": "#/$defs/isoDate"},
+        "effectiveTo": {"$ref": "#/$defs/isoDate"},
+        "retrievedAt": {"$ref": "#/$defs/isoDateTime"},
+        "canonicalUrl": {"type": "string", "format": "uri"},
+        "contentHash": {"type": "string", "minLength": 32},
+        "supersedes": {"$ref": "#/$defs/id"},
+        "reviewStatus": {"type": "string", "enum": ["captured", "verified", "rejected", "superseded"]}
+      },
+      "additionalProperties": false
+    },
+    "ruleVersion": {
+      "type": "object",
+      "required": ["id", "ruleId", "name", "version", "effectiveFrom", "status", "citations", "logicType"],
+      "properties": {
+        "id": {"$ref": "#/$defs/id"},
+        "ruleId": {"$ref": "#/$defs/id"},
+        "name": {"type": "string"},
+        "version": {"type": "integer", "minimum": 1},
+        "jurisdiction": {"type": "string"},
+        "effectiveFrom": {"$ref": "#/$defs/isoDate"},
+        "effectiveTo": {"$ref": "#/$defs/isoDate"},
+        "status": {"$ref": "#/$defs/status"},
+        "logicType": {"type": "string", "enum": ["deterministic", "attorney-judgment", "hybrid"]},
+        "inputs": {"type": "array", "items": {"type": "string"}},
+        "outputs": {"type": "array", "items": {"type": "string"}},
+        "citations": {"type": "array", "minItems": 1, "items": {"$ref": "#/$defs/citation"}},
+        "reviewedBy": {"type": "array", "items": {"type": "string"}},
+        "approvedAt": {"$ref": "#/$defs/isoDateTime"}
+      },
+      "additionalProperties": false
+    },
+    "change": {
+      "type": "object",
+      "required": ["id", "title", "detectedAt", "materiality", "sourceVersionIds", "affectedRuleVersionIds", "status"],
+      "properties": {
+        "id": {"$ref": "#/$defs/id"},
+        "title": {"type": "string"},
+        "detectedAt": {"$ref": "#/$defs/isoDateTime"},
+        "effectiveAt": {"$ref": "#/$defs/isoDateTime"},
+        "materiality": {"type": "string", "enum": ["critical", "high", "medium", "low", "watch"]},
+        "sourceVersionIds": {"type": "array", "minItems": 1, "items": {"$ref": "#/$defs/id"}},
+        "affectedRuleVersionIds": {"type": "array", "items": {"$ref": "#/$defs/id"}},
+        "status": {"type": "string", "enum": ["detected", "triaged", "scoped", "resolved", "dismissed"]}